observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
a. Municipal General Services Officer (GSO)//Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all PPE and submit the corresponding RPCPPE to the Accounting Office for reconciliation with accounting records and the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year for audit purposes;
b. MGSO and/or the Municipal Accountant to:
1. Complete the details of the PC and PPELC for each category of asset and reconcile both records;
2. Attend to the manpower needs in their respective Offices to manage PPE owned and controlled by the Municipality; and
3. Consider acquiring a computerized accounting system with the capability to generate audit trail reports, valuable information and financial statements such as the PPE Ledger Cards, depreciation schedule and details in General Ledger, as well as the ability to produce reports such as the Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) and Property Cards, among others, for easy identification and reconciliation of records;
c. Municipal Agriculturist to expedite the completion of the supporting documents and submit the same to the Auditor together with the request for relief from accountability. If not, demand payment from the person/s responsible for the loss of work animals; and
d. Municipal Accountant and the MGSO exert extra effort to determine the details of the unidentified PPE items totaling P66,509,276.83 following the guidelines and procedures of the “One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances” as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006.
We also recommended that the Management implement the “One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to establish verifiable PPE balances as to existence, condition and accountability.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct:
a. The MGSO to:
1. Conduct a physical count of inventories semestrally, generate/prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year;
2. Ensure the proper maintenance and accurate recording of each type of inventory in the Stock Card (SC);
3. Prepare Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for supplies and materials issued and consolidate all RIS using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit the same to the Municipal Accounting Office;
4. Reconcile the SCs periodically with the ledger cards of the Municipal Accountant; and
5. Reconcile the RPCI with the General Ledger (GL) controlling accounts;
b. Municipal Accountant to:
1. Maintain Supplies Ledger Cards for each commodity/stock and reconcile them with the GL controlling accounts; and
2. Reconcile Inventory accounts with RPCI; and
3. Draw a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the adjustments/corrections, if any.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct:
a. The designated MGSO to:
1. Conduct physical count of inventories semestrally, generate/prepare and submit the RPCI to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year;
2. Ensure the proper maintenance and accurate recording of each type of inventory in the SC;
3. Prepare RIS for supplies and materials issued and consolidate all RIS using the SSMI and submit the same to the Municipal Accounting Office;
4. Reconcile the SCs periodically with the ledger cards of the Municipal Accountant; and
5. Reconcile the RPCI with the General Ledger (GL) controlling accounts;
b. The Municipal Accountant to:
1. Maintain SLCs for each commodity/stock and reconcile them with the GL controlling accounts;
2. Reconcile Inventory accounts with RPCI; and
3. Draw a JEV to record the adjustments/corrections, if any.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor instruct
the Municipal Accountant to:
a. exert extra effort to expedite the retrieval of Memorandum of Agreement (MOA)
and other records to establish the details and purpose of the funds received
from National Government Agencies;
b. determine the details of the other accounts that remained unascertained;
c. see to it that all accounts appearing in the financial statements are properly
supported with subsidiary ledgers and supporting documents;
d. remit immediately to the source agencies all unexpended balances and savings
from identified completed projects funded by the National Government.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the MGSO to:
a.1 conduct physical count of inventories semestrally, generate/prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCIs) to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year.
a.2 properly maintain and observe correct recording in the SC for each type of inventory;
a.3 record all receipts and issuances of supplies in the stock cards;
a.4 prepare Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for supplies and materials issued and consolidate all RIS using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit the same to the Municipal Accounting Office;
a.5 reconcile the Stock Cards periodically with the ledger cards of Office of the Municipal Accountant; and
a.6 reconcile the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories with the GL controlling accounts.
b. the Municipal Accountant to:
b.1 maintain Supplies Ledger Cards for each commodity/stock which is to be reconciled with the GL controlling accounts;
b.2 reconcile Inventory accounts with RPCI; and
b.3 draw a Journal Entry Voucher to record the adjustments/corrections, if any.
